{"/service/ndnp/txdn/batch_txdn_evans_ver01/data/sn86063730/00332894195/1930021402/0257.xml":{"full_text":"lie InramstJl t Herald\nEstablished July 4, 1892\nEntered as second-class matter to the Post-office\nBrownsville, Texas.\nTHE CLOWNSVILLE HERAT,p PUBLISHING\nCOMPANY\nSubscription Bates\u2014Daily and Sunday (7 Issues)\nOne Ye\u00ab\nSix Months ...(iso\nThree Months..\nDne Month. .75\nMEMBER OF THE ASSOCIATED PRESS\nrhe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to the use\nlor publication of all news dispatches credited to it or\nnot otherwise credited to this paper, and also the\nlocal newi published hereto\nHarlingen Office, Reese-WU-Mond Hotel. Phone 1020.\nV-,\nTEXAS DAILY PRESS LEAGUE\nNational Advertising Representatives\nDallas. Texas, 512 Mercantile Bank Building.\nKansas City. Mo, 306 Coca Cola Building,\nChicago, 111, Association Building.\nNew York, 350 Madison Avenue.\nSL Louis. 502 Star Building.\nLos Angeles. CaL, Room 1015 New Orpheum Bldg,\n846 8. Broadway.\nSan Francisco, Cal, 318 Kohl Building.\nThe Valley and Immigration\nIf nothing more is done to help the immigration\nand labor situation in the Valley, it can be said\ntruthfully that much good has already been accom\nplished.\nFortunately, the work is just being launched on\nA systematic basis, and much greater benefits may\nbe expected.\nBut the work already done, and mainly by a few\npeople. It has brought attention to the subject,\nwhich in itself has helped. It has brought a closer\nrelation between the American and the Mexican\npeople living along the border. Americans who have\nlived here for years, and who Rave seldom talked to\nA Mexican in the course of business, have become\nclosely acquainted with some of the Valley s dti\n*ens who are of Mexican extraction.\nWhen the two peoples come to know one another\nmore closely, the misunderstandings between them\nwill vanish.\nThere has been a direct result toward accomplish\ning the goal that the Valley seeks\u2014in cutting down\nleportations of Mexicans.\nAt the time Cal. Sam Robertson, fighting Valley\npioneer who has had the courage and the willingness\nio stand up and battle the world in defense of his\n)ld Mexican friends, and a few others started the ac\ntivities against deportations there was occasion for\n>nmediate action.\nThousands of Mexicans were leaving voluntarily,\nscared half out of their wits by distorted reports of\nImprisonment, mistreatment and ultimate deporta\ntion under the new immigration laws.\nAfter the first few meetings in the Valley a sud\nden change in the situation resulted.\nThe Mexican people here began to have more con\nfidence. They calmed their fears, and decided to\nstay, since they had some friends among the Ameri\ncans.\nNow the deportations are being made at a much\nreduced rate, we are informed.\nThe question is by no means settled. Valley people\n\u2022till have a fight ahead of them to attempt to prevent\npassage of legislation which would cut down Mexi\ncan immigration to practically nothing.\nNo less an authority than J. T. Canales of Browns\nville says such a law would not check the tide of\nMexicans coming north, but would merely divert the\ntide from the farms to the federal prisons, which\nwould have to be considerably enlarged.\nIf there is anything we have enough of In this\ncountry now It is laws which can not be enforced.\nIt will do no harm to raise a vigorous protest against\nthe passage of one more such law.\nAway Down in Maine\nMaine was the first of the prohibition states. Al\nmost 80 years ago Gen. Neal Dow pioneered the com\nmonwealth Into the dry column. He paved the way\nand gave the sisterhood the first dry Sahara.\nSen. Arthur R. Gould Is retiring.\nFor Gov. Ralph O. Bruster who was the Idol of the\nklan In the not remote past is a candidate for the\nseat. Congressman Wallace H. White is another.\nAll are republicans. Du gal d B. Dewar has entered\na^mm^mmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmrnmmt mm\nthe list. He to a men of wealth and a dealer in\nInvestment securities.\nFor the first time In years In Maine an avowed\nwet to seeking the senatorial nomination of the re\npublican party. His war cry to that prohibition to\na flat failure and that the Volstead act should be\nrevised from top to bottom. There is something new\nunder the sun.\nit' Jill!\nThe Once Over\nBy H. L PHILLIPS\nWB\u2014a 77-= -s=s/<\nIS THERE NO JUSTICE?\n(Copyright, 1930, by The Associated Newspapers.)\nTake a deep breath, girls, and be as composed as\npossible while you hear the latest news? 'Don't get ex\ncited! Lisaen: Paris has come out for skirts with\nbathing suits!\nm\nJust when the daughters of our very best people\nhad become accustomed to parading up and down\nthe beaches looking Just about the way they looked\ngetting in and out of a bathtub, Patou will be the\nsmart thing this summer.\n\nThe situation calls for a revolution.\n\nUp. bathing girls, and at 'em!\n\u2022It\nAre you going to yield meekly and walk up and\ndown a beach so attired that nobody will turn around\nand lose a couple of eyes? Are you going to consent\nto go bathing in a costume that won\u2019t agitate a single\ncensor? Will you be satisfied to be seen at a shore\nresort In attire that even your best friend will agree\nis modest and decent?\n\nNo, ten thousand times no!\nYou know what will happen If you yield. Once\nthose Prench dressmakers get a skirt on a bathing\ngirl again they will some out for stockings. Then\nthere will be an edict that bathing-shoes are the\nsmart caper.\n\nAfter that\u2014Heaven forbid I Mons. Patou win come\nout for the old-fashioned blouse that mother used\nto wear.\n\nIt will be but a step from that to bathing-corsets,\na high collar and one of those big straw beach hats\nyou see In the family album when you turn to the\npicture of Aunt Arabella and Uncle Jim snapped with\nCousin Minnie and the pug dog at Glen Island the\nsummer before they blew up the Maine.\n\nIt will mean a return to the days when It took\nweeks for a nice girl to recover from the humiliation\nshe suffered when a male person saw her on the\nbathing beach with a run In her stocking.\n\nOr when young Otis Presbury noticed as she came\nout of the water that a half-inch of bare flesh showed\nbetween the tops of her stockings and her bloomers.\n\nOops, my dears!\n\nCall the protest meetings now before it is too late.\nThere are limits to what American womanhood will\nendure.\nCALIFORNIA PAPERS PLEASE COPY\n\u201cCharles Doerrer of Elm Street, who Is spending a\na few weeks in Miami. Florida, will celebrate his 680th\nbirthday there tomorrow.\"\u2014Plalnview, N. J. News.\nIt s Just Florida propaganda.\nADD DEPRESSING MOMENTS\nOne of the most depressing moments of life comes\nwhen you have bought two seats to a high-priced\nshow and then discovered that the press agent !s an\nold friend.\nTelephone companies complain that calls fall off\nheavily for months after a stock market crash. Most\nof us have been under the impression that calls in\ncreased and that every bond salesman in the world\ncalled up to ask. \"Well, do you realize how much bet\nter off you'd have been if you\u2019d bought what I sug\ngested?\u201d\nTHINGS I\u2019D LIKE TO HEAR FOR A CHANGE\nA Telephone Operator say: \"Shut Up. You Dope!\u201d\nA Walter answer: \"It\u2019s Not Very Nice.\u201d\nA Radio Announcer muff a broad \"Ah.\u201d\nA Traffic Cop stutter.\n\u2014In\u2019. Price.\nTHE OLD HOME TOWN Stanley\nII\nIU7F HE A\nup.\nMLU\nNO HES\nOCWN\ns*e\nMS OR\n\u2022THINS y\nt-\u2014\n^HUH -TALWAYS\nWONDERED WHY)\nDAD HAD \"THAT\nLAMP TRIGGED\nUPON \u201cTHAT\nL WURE\nold Dad Robinson didnt want visitors\nIN HIS STORE TO^SHOSE, SO HE USED 4\n..THIS METHOD TO QUIETLY^ AWAKEN\nTHEM WITHOUT OFFEND/Nfi^ OR UOS/N5\n_A CASH CUSTOMER.\n\nm qwTKM. rmm\u25a0\u00bb\nCHAPTER 44\n\u201cWe\u2019ve been waiting, too Madame\nLeclerct But we must get together.\nYou had better come right over\nhere at once! Grab a taxi and make\nIt snappy,\" ordered Rex Dailard.\nShe made it snappy. That was, in\nfact, the order she gave the taxi\ndriver. He made the run from 47th\nstreet and Broadway to the Gram\nercy Park House in double quick\ntime. Just before she arrived and\nduring an animated discussion on\nthe probability of this and the pos\nsibility of that a horrifying thought;\nsuddenly struck Pat. What if Max-\nwell, or one of his hirelings had\nseen the departure of Margery and\nherself from the Lynne home with\nout Jimmy\u2014?\n\u2022Oh!\u201d she gasped. The exclama\ntion drew the attention of the oth\ners who stared at her wonderingly.\n\"Jimmy!\u201d she gulped, her lips\nwhite with the sudden fearsome\npossibility that had occured to her\nas to what might have happened\nin the two and a half hours since\nthey had ledt him. Her fear-shot eyes\ncaught sight of the telephone. Mar\ngery noted the glance and inter\npreted Instantly the dread thought\nthat had partially paralyzed the\nother girl's actions.\nShe fairly tore across the room\nto the table, grabbed up the tele\nphone and gave the number of her\nown home. The three men by this\ntime had grasped the meaning of\nthe sudden interruption to the talk\nand stood waiting, their eyes as\nwell as Pat\u2019s riveted on Margery,\nwho also waited, tense, rigid.\nThen It came, the signal sputter,\nfollowed bv a voice, that of Aunt\nLottie, calm and clear as usual.\nMargery\u2019s rigidity vanished. But\nher voice shook as she spoke.\n\"Tell me quick. Aunt Lottie\u2014is\nJimmy where you can see him right\nnow? You know we told you\u2014\u201d\n\u201cJimm?*s sitting right here in the\nroom playing with his fingers. Just\nas he has been doing ever since you\nleft the house!\u201d came the impatient\nbut satisfying reply. Then: \u201cIs that\nall you wanted to know?\u201d\n\u201cYes, yes. Aunty dear!\u201d Margery\nanswered In a voice that still trem\nbled a little in the aftermath of re\nlief. \u201cBut we just received one piece\nof bad news and it occurred to Pat\nthat we might have another await\ning us. Thank the Lord he's safe.\nJust do as we told you, dear\u2014\ndon\u2019t let a soul into the house un\nless you know who \u2019tis and don\u2019t\nlet Jimmy even leave the room!\nThats\u2019 all!\u201d\nShe placed the telephone back on\nthe table. Then she turned slowly, j\nlooking at Pat and then at the\nothers.\n\u201cThat should be a warning to us!\u201d\nshe said ominously. \"We\u2019ve had\nproof enough, the Lord knows, of\nT~\nGrab Bag\nFebruary 14, 1930\nWho am I? To what post have\nI been named? In what similar\ncapacity did I serve under President\nHardin*?\nWho vu Virginia Dare?\nIn what state Is the Teapot Dome\noil field?\n\"Far the needy shall not alway\nbe forgotten: the expectation of the\npoor shall not perish for ever.\"\nWhere is this passage found In the\nBible?\nCorrectly Speaking\u2014\nWhen the subject Is In the first\nperson, the auxiliary verb should\nalways be \u2018shall\u201d or \"should\u201d, ex\ncept In repeating a question ad- i\ndressed to the speaker, then \u2018\u2018wlH\u201d j\nis used.\nToday's Anniversary\nToday is the anniversary\u2019 of the\ndeath of St. Valentine.\nToday's Horoscope\nPersons born on this day are very\nlovable but selfish. They demand a\ngreat deal of attention.\nAnswers to Foregoing Questions\n1. Edward E. Brodie: minister to\nFinland; minister to 8iam.\n2. First white child born in Amer\nica.\n3. Wyoming.\n4. Psalm lx. 18.\nI Star Lor el\nSATURN\u2019S STORY TOLD BY A\nSPECTOGRAM\nBy Arthur DeV. Carpenter\nThe spectroscopic photograph of\nthe ball and rings of Saturn tells\nan interesting story. The east half\nof the planet and rings show ver\ntical lines shifted toward the left\nor violet, as compared with a stat\nionary spectrum, because they are\nrotating toward you, while the west\nhalf, because away from you. are\nshifted toward the red or right, j\nThen because the earth was ap\nproaching Saturn at the time, the\nlines of the east half are still more\nintensely shifted toward the violet\nThe lines of the inner edge of the\nring are displaced more than those\nof the outer edge, showing the in\nner part of the ring is rotating\nmore rapidly than the outer.\n(More Tomorrow)\nI\nthe desperate things Maxwell Is\ncapable of doing I He has kidnaped\nboth Pat and Jimmy once, and now\n\u2014oh, dear!\u201d She wrung her hands\nwith a quick, spasmodic little twist\nthat made the knuckles crack.\n\"Can't something be done to that\nold wretch? Can\u2019t he be arrested\nfor abduction or\u2014or something?\u201d\nBefore anyone could offer any\nsolution to the problem of supresa\ning Maxwell's pernicious activities\na knock on the door announced the\narrival of Madame Leclerc.\nThere was a look in the woman's\ngreat dark eyes as she dropped\nwearily Into the chair Dr. Gordon\npushed forward that told not only\nof a desperate anxiety, but was.ac\ntually foreboding in its effect.\nAgain Pat felt a surge of sympathy\nwell up In her heart for this Aus\ntria ex-spy, whose deep love for\nher husband had brought her three\nthousand miles on a mission that\nseemed so utterly futile to one\nknowing Herbert Maxwell. What\nreason could Madame Leclerc have\nfor thinking she could persuade\nthat ruthless traitor to his own\nland, a man totally devoid of hu\nman feeling, to help her in a mat\nter where his own personal liberty\nwas periled? It was folly to hope\nfor anything from him. Pat told\nherself in her swift inventory of\nthe woman's tragic looks and pros\npects. Her momentary musing was\ninterrupted by the voice of Rex\nDallard as he addressed the late\ncomer.\n\"You said the chambermaid at\nthe apartment house told you that\nyoung Bouchard had not been In\nhis room since early last nigh*,\u201d\nRex began, getting to his point\nwithout any circumlocution. \u201cHow\ncould she be sure of that? Does\nshe know he\u2019s connected with Max\nwell, who you said, lives at the\nsame place?'\n\u201cThat\u2019s how she happened to\nknow Jean wasn\u2019t in his room last\nnight said Madame Leclerc. try- j\ning to answer the three questions\nat once. \"Maxwell had asked her\nto throw the few things on Jean\u2019s\ndresser and in the drawers Into\nhis bag and bring the bag to him\u2014\nthat they were leaving immediately\nfor California. He told her that Jean\nhad stayed with a friend the night\nbefore and would meet him at the\nstation! I called up the manager\nof the apartment house right after\nmy talk with you and he verified\nthe maid\u2019s statement: said the\n'Maxwell party,' as he called them.\nhad left this morning without a\nmoment's notice, being called to i\nCalifornia on urgent business. U's\na lie on Maxwell\u2019s part, of course!\u201d\nsnapped the woman at the finish,\nan angry light burning in her black\neyes.\n\u201cIt certainly puts a new kink In\nthe skein of affairs, there\u2019s no\nquestion about that!\u201d averred Rex,\nwith a grim tightening of the lips.\nHe seemed to ponder the matter\nfor a brief moment. Then he shot\na keen glance at Madame Leclerc.\n\"Has it occurred to you. Madame?\u201d\nhe queried cautiously, 'that there\nmight be a possibility of young\nBouchard being hooked up in an\nother conspiracy with Maxwell?\u201d\nShe glanced up quickly, a trifle\nstartled, apparently at the question.\n\u201cDo you mean he may be double\ncrossing us\u2014that he's working In\nMaxwell\u2019s and not our interests?\u201d\nshe asked.\n\"I\u2019m not saving that he Is: I'm\nonly asking If it has occurred to\nyou that there is a possibility of\nsuch a conspiracy?\u201d answered Rex.\n\"No. for I'm sure there isn\u2019t!\u201d\nreplied Madame Leclerc with an\nemphasis, there was no mistaking.\n\u201cI\u2019m certain that Jean\u2019s failure to\nmeet me.today is not owing to any\nconnivance on his part with Her\nbert Maxwell. He was either held\nup in the taxi after leaving me. and\nkilled, and his body secreted some\nwhere, or else he's been kidnaped\nby some of Maxy\u2019s hirelings to keep\nhim from aiding Miss Blair! With\nJean out of the way and the securi\nties hidden where only Maxwell\ncan get at them, what can she do?\nHe's got the money, and possession\nyou know, is always nine points of\nthe law. She can do nothing, es\npecially now that he, too, has disap\npeared. Can she?\u201d\nIt was a question that none\namong them, including the lawyer,\nseemed able to answer.\n\"It strikes me.\u201d said Dr Gordon,\nafter a moment's silence following\nthe woman\u2019s unanswerable question,\n\"that affairs have reached a sort\nof climax\u2014a state where the pollc.e\nought to be notified. I don\u2019t sup\npose we could have Maxwell arrest\ned. even if we could find him. on a\ncharge of abduction, but we can\nreport the strange disappearance\nof young Bouchard and tell the\npolloe our reasons for suspecting\nfoul play! And I think, too. that\nPat ought to hire a couple of de- i\nHOPE SPRINGS ETERNAL\nBE MY\n(valentine!]\ntectives to keep watch on the Lyn\nne home, day and night, as a pro\ntection to Jimmy. For I think, like\nMargery, that we should take no\nchance where Old Maxy is concern\ned. He's given us proof enough. Just\nas she says, of his deviltry. What\nhe\u2019s done before he's very likely to\ndo again, if he is given any chance!\u201d\nAll of which, as everyone. Includ\ning the lawyer, very quickly agreed,\nwas nothing less than good logic.\nHaving arrived at this conclusion\nwithout a dissenting voice it was\nunanimously voted to put the de\ncision into execution at once.\nAs a result, the big limousine that\nhad brought Pat and Margery over\nin lonely grandeur to the Gram\nercy Park House, conveyed a party\nof six besides the chauffeur, down\nLafayette street to Police Head\nquarters.\nAs a further result of the deci\nsion and thanks to the lawyer s\nacquaintance with the desk ser\ngeant, Michael Kelly, then on duty,\nthe unaccountable disappearnce of\nJean Bouchard, together with its\nclose connection with Patricia\nBlair's affairs, which included the\nremoval bv trickery of fourteen\nmillion dollars in security receiv\ned immediate attention.\n(TO BE CONTINUED)\nVISITS CITY\nNick McCarty, Harlingen, owner\nof the Jitney Jungle stores there\nand in Brownsville, was business\nvisitor In Brownsville Thursday\nafternoon.\nU I I I I \u2014f\n[ATTENTION!\nWe have added a I\nRental Library to our\nstore! Come in and look\nI it over. All of the best X\nsellers of all publishers.\nKeep abreast of the t\nmost popular new books\nby renting them at\nsmall cost!\nI HARGROVE\u2019S\nI Stationery Book Store\nL Phone 348\nBrownsville, Texas g\n'A cry in the night may be the\nfirst warning that Baby has colic.\nNo cause for alarm if Castoria is\nhandy 1 This pure vegetable prep\naration brings quick comfort, and\ncan never do the slightest harm.\nAlways keep a bottle in the house.\nIt is the safe and sensible thing\nwhen children are ailing. Whether\nit\u2019s the stomach, or the little\nbowels; colic or constipation; or\ndiarrhea. When tiny tongues are\ncoated, or the breath is bad.\nWhenever there\u2019s need of gentle\nregulation, Children love the\ntaste of Castoria. and its mildness\nmakes it suitable for the tiniest\ninfant, and for frequent use.\nAnd a more liberal dose of\nCastoria is always better for\ngrowing children than some need\nlessly strong medicine meant only\nfor adult use. Genuine Castoria\nalways has Chas. H. Fletcher\u2019s\nsignature on the wrapper. Pre\nscribed by doctors t\nChicago Club Hears\nLecture on Valley\n\u201cOut of the snow and Ice Into\nthe sunny Valley of the Rio Grande\nbegins a news item in the\nChicago Daily News of recent date.\nCitizens of uie second largest\ncity in the nation are beginning to\nnotice Brownsville and the Valley, it\nwas said, and the Garfield Club of\nChicago devoted an evening to an\nillustrated lecture on this section.\nCol. P. E. Holp gave the talk, Thos.\nR. Heaney is president of the club.\nNo fewer than 26.429 inspections\nby government officials were made\nin Italian factories last year.\nEat At\nAnthony\u2019s Waffle\nShop\n517 12 St Phone 983\nA. TAMM\nBlue Printing and\nSupplies\nHarlingen, Texas\n1911 1930\nSkelton Abstract Co.\nAbstracts of Title Title Insurance\nMerchants Bank Building Brownsville\nDependable Phone 353 Prompt\nBROWNSVILLE TITLE COMPANY\nBROWNSVILLE. TEXAS\nAbstracts of Title Title Insurance\nWe cover all lands In Cameron County\nCARNEIRO, CHUMNEY COMPANY\nCertified Public Accountants\nIncome Tax Service\nBROWNSVILLE SAN ANTONIO CORPUS CHRI8TI\nState National Bank Smith-Young Tower Nixon Building\nfKOSPERm\nProsperity for Brownsville and\nthe Valley is a tangible, able-to\nbe-seen condition. Citrus groves\nare beginning to bloom vege\ntables are commanding good\nprices generally the interna\ntional airport and the bright\nprospects for a deep water port\u2014\nall are encouraging a splendid\nbusiness outlook for Brownsville\nand the Valley.\nLet us, as your bank, help\nyou with any problems you\nmay wish to discuss with us.\nFirst National Bank\nEstablished in 1891\nBROWNSVILLE, TEXAS\nTITLE INSURANCE\nWhen you borrow money on real estate, many loan companies re\nquire the title to be insured. Ihe best test of whether a title is\nInsurable, is to have it insured. Require a title insurance policy\nwhen you buy.\nVALLEY ABSTRACT COMPANY\nPrompt Title Service\nBrownsville Fdinburr\nOopcsite Court IIcue E llarriman Blvd.\nPhone 1184 *'*\u00bbone 93","height":"36240","width":"27092"}}
